git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your-email@gmail.com"

git config --global --list

cd /c/Users/YourName/Desktop (I didn't use it)

git clone https://github.com/USERNAME/REPO_NAME.git
cd REPO_NAME.git
.git - brain of git
git init- Git creates a hidden folder called .git/(Keeps history, versions, and rules). Creates normal folder to Git repo
vim shellscripting.sh (save & exit)
git status (You’ll see: untracked → new file || modified → edited file)
git add shellscripting.sh
.git/hooks/pre-commit - pre-commit is an automatic check that runs before Git saves your commit.
git commit -m "Add the shell script"
git pull origin main
git push
git checkout - lets you move to another branch or undo uncommitted changes.
git log - list of logs
git remote -v - shows the GitHub (remote) URLs your repo talks to
git remote add <name> <url>
Fork - A fork is your own copy of someone else’s repository on GitHub
